===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{liushu|j}} of {{och-l|鳳|fenghuang}} borrowed for sound to represent {{och-l|風|wind}}. The right part of the bronze inscription of the character consists of phonetic {{och-l|凡}} at the top, and three parts depicting the fur on the tail of the male ''fenghuang'' at the bottom.

Subsequent forms of {{lang|zh|風}} are based on the right part of its bronze inscription, with two of the three threads of "fur" removed for simplification. The {{zh-l|虫}} in the Chu script and Qin script of {{lang|zh|風}} was likely a result of further simplification of the "fur".

''{{w|Shuowen}}'' misinterpreted the character {{lang|zh|風}} by associating it with insects. ({{zh-ref|Li, 2012}})

===Etymology===
Possibly from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*buŋ||wind}} (STEDT). Velar nasal final ''-ŋ'', restored later in Middle Chinese ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}), is preserved in cognates like Proto-Central Naga ''*m-puŋ'', {{cog-lite|kac|mabung}}, {{m-lite|kac|nbung}}, {{cog-lite|duu|nvmbeung}}.

Pronunciations 1, 2, and 3 are all cognates; with both 2 and 3 evolving from ''*prəm-s'', exoactive (with causative suffix ''-s'') of ''*prəm'' ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). It is unclear how Old Chinese ''*prəm'' is related to {{cog|bo|རླུང}} and {{cog|tai-pro|*C̬.lɯmᴬ}}.

{{cog|ko|바람}} may have been borrowed from Chinese ({{zh-ref|Zhao, 2007}}). The Chinese word has a wide range of extended meanings, and interestingly many of these have exact parallels in the Korean item. Compare Chinese {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|風流}} and {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|風騷}} with Korean {{m|ko|바람둥이}}.

Cognate with:
* {{och-l|飛廉|gloss=wind god}}
* {{och-l|蜚蠊|gloss=cockroach}} (note the preservation of the ''-r-'' infix in Old Chinese through disyllabification, also {{och-l|嵐}}, {{och-l|葻}})
* {{och-l|瘋|gloss=mad, insane}}
* {{och-l|諷|gloss=to mock, to advise}}
* {{och-l|帆|gloss=sail}}

The development from Old Chinese to Middle Chinese was irregular, driven by {{w|dissimilation}} of the initial and coda bilabial consonants.

